Ecommerce-Purchase-Prediction
Predicting E-commerce purchases using Machine learning, and customer segmentation for targeted marketing

Dataset
The data was sourced from Harvard Dataverse, the dataset is titled ‘Open e-commerce 1.0: Five years of crowdsourced U.S. Amazon purchase histories with user demographics’. This dataset contains longitudinal purchases data from 5027 Amazon.com users in the US, spanning 2018 through 2022. It also includes demographic data and other consumer level variables for each user, which were collected through an online survey.

Implementation
View the full project report here

Dataset preparation and Exploratory Data Analysis The dataset is preprocessed using Pandas in Python.
A subset of the customers was selected, to include only residents of California to simplify the processing.

Data cleaning

Target feature transformation: The target feature is defined as a binary variable of whether or not a customer would make a purchase in the next 60 days.

Feature engineering RFM (Recency, Frequency and Monetary) features are created per customer based on their purchase histories, for further cluster analysis.

Cluster analysis Cluster Analysis is performed to cluster the customers by their survey responses and RFM features, to analyse purchasing behaviour. Rapid Miner was used to create the clustering workflow, using K Means clustering. The resulting 5 clusters showed important demographic andpurchasiing insights.

ML Modeling The RFM cluster prediction is included as a feature for the ML model to predict future purchases.
RapidMiner was used to create a Machine Learning model for binary classification, using Auto model for automated ML model training and performance analysis.

Evaluation
Evaluation by comparing model performance using ROC curves showed that GLM model (Generalized Linear Model) performed the best.
Below are the performance metrics of the GLM model:
• AUC = 0.962
• Precision = 0.908
• Recall = 0.971
• F-Measure = 0.938

